{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17634313","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17634313"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:58:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:58:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17508"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17508","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17508"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.45,0.15,0.05,0,0.35]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10198"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78058"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10198","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10198"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17508"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63480"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10053"},{"type":"tags","id":"10067"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23867"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23876"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78058","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78058"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the first enzymatic step of glycogenolysis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Conversion of glucose-1-phosphate to glucose-6-phosphate","Removal of \u03b1-1,6 branch points by debranching enzyme","Phosphorylation of glucose by glucokinase","Hydrolysis of glycogen by amylase","Cleavage of \u03b1-1,4 glycosidic bonds by glycogen phosphorylase"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGlycogenolysis is the breakdown of stored glycogen to glucose-1-phosphate to maintain blood glucose levels. The first step is catalysed by \u003Cstrong\u003Eglycogen phosphorylase\u003C/strong\u003E, which cleaves \u03b1-1,4 glycosidic bonds from the non-reducing ends of glycogen chains to release glucose-1-phosphate. This enzyme is regulated by hormones including glucagon and adrenaline through cyclic AMP-dependent protein kinase A phosphorylation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERemoval of \u03b1-1,6 branch points by debranching enzyme\u003C/strong\u003E - This occurs after glycogen phosphorylase action when branch points are reached\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConversion of glucose-1-phosphate to glucose-6-phosphate\u003C/strong\u003E - This is catalysed by phosphoglucomutase after glucose-1-phosphate release\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydrolysis of glycogen by amylase\u003C/strong\u003E - Amylase is involved in dietary carbohydrate digestion, not glycogenolysis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhosphorylation of glucose by glucokinase\u003C/strong\u003E - This enzyme phosphorylates free glucose during glycolysis, not glycogenolysis\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe sequential action of glycogen phosphorylase and debranching enzyme allows for efficient mobilisation of glucose units from glycogen stores when needed for energy production.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Glycogen phosphorylase catalyses the first step of glycogenolysis by cleaving glucose-1-phosphate from glycogen chains.","Glycogen phosphorylase is activated by glucagon and adrenaline via cyclic AMP-dependent protein kinase A.","Glycogenolysis provides rapid glucose release during fasting and exercise."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Patino SC, Orrick JA. Biochemistry - Glycogenolysis. [Updated 2024 Jan 27]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan. Available from: https://www.statpearls.com/","Nelson DL, Cox MM. Lehninger Principles of Biochemistry. 7th ed. New York: W.H. Freeman and Company; 2017."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63480"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17508"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63480","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63480"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-09T12:17:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-09T12:18:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10198"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78058"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":